<subSubSection id="9BBC3DF6B108FFC2FD3C7516AC067C80" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D3196E7DB108FFC2FD3C7516AC067C80" blockId="28.[701,1228,313,1754]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
DIAGNOSIS: Because the 
<typeStatus id="0C1DD0DFB108FFC2FC1D7516AB687E6D" box="[1017,1065,313,337]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">type</typeStatus>
species of this genus has been known only from females, and no illustrations were provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FB66755BAC577E96" author="Simon, E." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="65 - 80" refId="ref20875" refString="Simon, E. 1893 b. Arachnides. In: Voyage de M. E. Simon aux ˆles i Philipines (mars et avril 1890). 6 e memoire. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France 62: 65 - 80." type="journal article" year="1893">Simon (1893b)</bibRefCitation>
, the identity and relationships of the taxon have remained obscure. Simon did recognize the affinity of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FC3D75E2ABD17ED9" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[985,1168,461,485]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FC3D75E2ABD17ED9" box="[985,1168,461,485]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Epectris apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FD5975C5AC617D3E" box="[701,800,490,514]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FD5975C5AC617D3E" box="[701,800,490,514]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and might well have placed the species in 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FCD47627ACD27D1C" box="[816,915,520,544]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FCD47627ACD27D1C" box="[816,915,520,544]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead had he known that the male palpal patella shares the synapomorphies of that genus. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FBC0766CAB8A7D67" author="Simon, E." box="[1060,1227,579,603]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="257 - 488" refId="ref20853" refString="Simon, E. 1893 a. Histoire naturelle des araignees. Paris: Roret, 1: 257 - 488." type="journal article" year="1893">Simon (1893a)</bibRefCitation>
separated 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FCD7764FACCF7D44" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[819,910,608,632]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FCD7764FACCF7D44" box="[819,910,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Epectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FC32764FAB787D44" box="[982,1081,608,632]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FC32764FAB787D44" box="[982,1081,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of its more procurved posterior eye row (figs. 111, 113, 115, 117). Males can easily be separated from those of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FBE77696AB277DED" box="[1027,1126,697,721]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FBE77696AB277DED" box="[1027,1126,697,721]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a long basal protrusion on the palpal bulb (fig. 151), and both sexes have a posterior dark spot on the abdominal dorsum (figs. 105, 108) that is lacking in 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FBD77700ABD77C7B" box="[1075,1174,815,839]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FBD77700ABD77C7B" box="[1075,1174,815,839]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but these differences, like those in the eye pattern, may be just highly autapomorphic characters of the 
<typeStatus id="0C1DD0DFB108FFC2FCC977A9AC1C7CA2" box="[813,861,902,926]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">type</typeStatus>
species (see below, under Synonymy).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9BBC3DF6B108FFC3FD3C77EDAECD7D75" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph id="D3196E7DB108FFC2FD3C77EDAC437B29" blockId="28.[701,1228,313,1754]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
DESCRIPTION: A description has been provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FCC977CFABE57CC4" author="Saaristo, M. I. &amp; Y. M. Marusik" box="[813,1188,992,1016]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="17 - 53" refId="ref20744" refString="Saaristo, M. I., and Y. M. Marusik. 2008. A survey of African Opopaea Simon, 1891 (Arachnida, Araneae, Oonopidae). Arthropoda Selecta 17: 17 - 53." type="journal article" year="2008">Saaristo and Marusik (2008: 39</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FD5977D2ADB37B29" box="[701,754,1021,1045]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Nale" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FD5977D2ADB37B29" box="[701,754,1021,1045]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Nale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3196E7DB108FFC2FD3C7034ABF97914" blockId="28.[701,1228,313,1754]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
MISPLACED SPECIES: Two modern species have been placed in the genus: 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FB947016ACB57B52" authority="Brignoli (1978)" authorityName="Brignoli" authorityYear="1978" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aenobarbus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FB947016AC7B7B53" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Epectris aenobarbus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FCA27079ACB57B52" author="Brignoli, P. M." box="[838,1012,1110,1134]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="31 - 56" refId="ref19981" refString="Brignoli, P. M. 1978. Ergebnisse der Bhutan-Expedition 1972 des Naturhistorischen Museums in Basel. Araneae: Fam. Oonopidae, Agelenidae, Hahniidae und Mimetidae. Entomologica Basiliensia 3: 31 - 56." type="journal article" year="1978">Brignoli (1978)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="ABB12EEDB108FFC2FBA67079ABD77B52" box="[1090,1174,1110,1134]" name="Bhutan" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bhutan</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FD59705BAB797BB0" authority="Xu (1986)" authorityName="Xu" authorityYear="1986" box="[701,1080,1140,1164]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conujaingensis">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FD59705BACFF7BB0" box="[701,958,1140,1164]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Epectris conujaingensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FC22705BAB797BB0" author="Xu, Y. J." box="[966,1080,1140,1164]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="270 - 273" refId="ref21009" refString="Xu, Y. J. 1986. Two new species of oonopid spiders from China (Araneae: Oonopidae). Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica 11: 270 - 273." type="journal article" year="1986">Xu (1986)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="ABB12EEDB108FFC2FB9B705BAB867BB0" box="[1151,1223,1140,1164]" name="China" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">China</collectingCountry>
, but it is clear from the palpal illustrations provided by those authors that both of those species are misplaced, and are not congeneric with the 
<typeStatus id="0C1DD0DFB108FFC2FCD670C5AC237A3E" box="[818,866,1258,1282]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">type</typeStatus>
species of either 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FBAC70C5ABE27A3E" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[1096,1187,1258,1282]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FBAC70C5ABE27A3E" box="[1096,1187,1258,1282]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Epectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FD597128AC617A23" box="[701,800,1287,1311]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FD597128AC617A23" box="[701,800,1287,1311]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The only other species currently assigned to the genus is 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FC30710AAC467A66" authority="Simon (1907)" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1907" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FC30710AAB3B7A01" box="[980,1146,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Epectris mollis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FB66710AAC467A66" author="Simon, E." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="246 - 264" refId="ref20921" refString="Simon, E. 1907. Etude sur les araignees de la soussection des Haplogynes. Annales de la Soc Societe Entomologique de Belgique 51: 246 - 264." type="journal article" year="1907">Simon (1907)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, based on a female from 
<collectingCountry id="ABB12EEDB108FFC2FBA8716DAB867A66" box="[1100,1223,1346,1370]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
; Simon provided no illustrations, but his indication that the abdomen lacks scuta shows that this species is also misplaced, possibly even at the subfamily level. The affinities of all three taxa will remain uncertain until their 
<typeStatus id="0C1DD0DFB108FFC2FD5971DCADB97937" box="[701,760,1523,1547]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">types</typeStatus>
can be examined in the course of revisionary studies on Old World oonopids.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3196E7DB108FFC3FD3C7200AECD7D75" blockId="28.[701,1228,313,1754]" lastBlockId="29.[88,614,210,585]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
SYNONYMY: 
<bibRefCitation id="B737138CB108FFC2FC977200AB8A797B" author="Saaristo, M. I. &amp; Y. M. Marusik" box="[883,1227,1583,1607]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="17 - 53" refId="ref20744" refString="Saaristo, M. I., and Y. M. Marusik. 2008. A survey of African Opopaea Simon, 1891 (Arachnida, Araneae, Oonopidae). Arthropoda Selecta 17: 17 - 53." type="journal article" year="2008">Saaristo and Marusik (2008)</bibRefCitation>
removed 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FCCD7263AC3D7958" box="[809,892,1612,1636]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lena">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FCCD7263AC3D7958" box="[809,892,1612,1636]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">O. lena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FC237263AB6B7958" box="[967,1066,1612,1636]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FC237263AB6B7958" box="[967,1066,1612,1636]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and placed it in the monotypic new genus 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FC1A7245AB7279BE" box="[1022,1075,1642,1666]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Nale" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FC1A7245AB7279BE" box="[1022,1075,1642,1666]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Nale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, arguing that the remaining species of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FC0272A8AB0879A3" box="[998,1097,1671,1695]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FC0272A8AB0879A3" box="[998,1097,1671,1695]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are united by a palpal fenestra that is lacking in 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FB97728AAB857981" box="[1139,1220,1701,1725]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lena">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FB97728AAB857981" box="[1139,1220,1701,1725]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">O. lena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Because 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB108FFC2FCF972EDAC2D79E6" box="[797,876,1730,1754]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lena">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB108FFC2FCF972EDAC2D79E6" box="[797,876,1730,1754]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">O. lena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior synonym of the 
<typeStatus id="0C1DD0DFB108FFC2FB7872EDAB8D79E6" box="[1180,1228,1730,1754]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FF3174FCAE6F7FD7" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[213,302,211,235]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FF3174FCAE6F7FD7" box="[213,302,211,235]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Epectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FEA674FCAE377FD7" box="[322,374,211,235]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Nale" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FEA674FCAE377FD7" box="[322,374,211,235]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Nale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here placed as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FEC974DFAEC77E34" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[301,390,240,264]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FEC974DFAEC77E34" box="[301,390,240,264]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Epectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We suspect that 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FDA974DFAFEB7E19" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FDA974DFAFEB7E19" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">E. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is just a highly autapomorphic species of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FF9F7505AF9D7E7E" box="[123,220,298,322]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FF9F7505AF9D7E7E" box="[123,220,298,322]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, rather than its sister group, and that 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FF6B7567AFA97E5C" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[143,232,328,352]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FF6B7567AFA97E5C" box="[143,232,328,352]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Epectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FEC27567AE1B7E5C" box="[294,346,328,352]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Nale" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FEC27567AE1B7E5C" box="[294,346,328,352]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Nale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may both therefore be junior synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FEAE754AAEEA7E41" box="[330,427,357,381]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FEAE754AAEEA7E41" box="[330,427,357,381]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A decision on that question should wait until the Old World fauna is fully revised and the relationships of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FDA975B0AFEB7EE8" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FDA975B0AFEB7EE8" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">E. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the many species of 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FE5C7593AD587EE8" box="[440,537,444,468]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FE5C7593AD587EE8" box="[440,537,444,468]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Opopaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be analyzed in detail, using both morphological and molecular data. It seems likely, though, that 
<taxonomicName id="14A615FEB109FFC3FF77763BAE4D7D10" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[147,268,532,556]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Epectris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="E1D2B26FB109FFC3FF77763BAE4D7D10" box="[147,268,532,556]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">E. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does actually have a palpal fenestra (see figs. 155, 156).
</paragraph>
